187":"1187","1198":"1198","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1192":"1192","1170":"1170","1228":"1228","1215":"1215","1168":"1168","1266":"1266","1218":"1218","1207":"1207","Bradwell, Suffolk, England":"Bradwell, Suffolk, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","France":"France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Avilliers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Etienne, Andre, Raoul.  Dutch Adriaan, Willem.","French: variant, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, of   Villiers  . Compare   Devillers   and   Devillier  .","History: The progenitor of the majority of the American bearers of the surname <i>Devilliers</i> or <i>De Villiers</i> was Nicolas-Antoine Coulon, <i>sieur/chevalier</i> de Villiers, from France, who arrived in QC in 1703. In 1705, he married Angélique Jarret de Verchères. He was an officer in the French army. His descendants also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Devillers</i> and <i>Devillier</i>, and also the surname   Jumonville  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Villiers","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Villiers, the name of several places in France, all named from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’ (see   Villars  ). Compare   Devilliers  ."]},{"name":"Devillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cecile, Jacques, Maudry, Raoul.","French: variant of   Devilliers   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","History: The (majority of the) American bearers of the surname <i>Devillier</i> are descendants of Nicolas-Antoine Coulon, <i>sieur</i> de Villiers, from France (see   Devilliers  )."]},{"name":"Jumonville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcee, Jean-Paul, Marcel.","French: topographic name shortened from the title <i>sieur de Jumonville</i>, which refers to Jumeauville, a place in Yvelines. The surname <i>Jumonville</i> is not found in France.","History: Joseph Coulon de Villiers, <i>sieur</i> de Jumonville, a son of Nicolas-Antoine Coulon, <i>sieur</i> de Villiers, from France (see   Devilliers  ), married Marie-Marguerite Soumande in Montreal, QC, in 1745."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":28,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John d'Avilliers was born in 1187, in Bradwell, Suffolk, England, his father, Adam d'Avillers II, was 19 and his mother, Mrs. Petronell De Villiers of Hohenberg, was 17. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1218, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1187–1218":"1187–1218","1194–Male":"1194–Surnud","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1207–1266":"1207–1266","1168–1228":"1168–1228","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","about 1193":"umbes 1193","1187":"1187","1198":"1198","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1192":"1192","1170":"1170","1228":"1228","1215":"1215","1168":"1168","1266":"1266","1218":"1218","1207":"1207","Bradwell, Suffolk, England":"Bradwell, Suffolk, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United K